<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Best Hoop Spacing for a 4x8 Bed</h2>

  <p>
    Even spacing across the bed prevents sagging and keeps the cloth stable.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>place hoops at regular intervals along the 8-foot length</li>
    <li>ensure edges are supported</li>
    <li>avoid large gaps between hoops</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Consistent spacing improves both strength and coverage.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How High Should Hoops Be?</h2>

  <p>
    Hoop height should match the crop and growth stage. Lower tunnels retain heat better, while higher tunnels allow for plant growth and airflow.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most early-season crops, a moderate height works best.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Spacing Hoops Too Far Apart</h3>
  <p>
    This causes sagging and weak points in the structure.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Hoops That Are Too Weak</h3>
  <p>
    Leads to collapse under wind or snow load.
  </p>

  <h3>Ignoring Edge Support</h3>
  <p>
    Ends are often the most vulnerable points.
  </p>

  <h3>Choosing the Wrong Height</h3>
  <p>
    Too low restricts growth, too high reduces protection.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Set Up Hoops Properly</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Install hoops evenly across the bed.</li>
    <li>Ensure each hoop is firmly anchored.</li>
    <li>Lay frost cloth over the structure.</li>
    <li>Secure edges tightly to prevent wind entry.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    A stable frame makes the entire system more effective.
  </p>
</section>

